<dl id="n03062f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03062f">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03062f"> 62(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> a slip of a boy ~ <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03062f"><li>FW 42.29 </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/lexb.htm#n03062f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/l39b.htm#n03062f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03062f">MS BL 47471b-1v</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:026 <a name="b20d" href="../../FF/fdra/bda.htm#b20d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/b/b20d.htm#n03062f">Draft: I.2&sect;2.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The little crowd were at hand. The old man stepped outside the wicket and the opening was a narrow one and he stood helplessly by, bent down like the bough of an ancient tree. &ldquo;Michael,&rdquo; he said to Michael Keohane, who, he knew, was captain over them; &ldquo;ah, Michael, he&apos;s only a boy, <mark>a slip of a boy</mark>.&rdquo; But Keohane, who for the past few years had had always more problems to decide upon than he was able to come at, had acquired a quick and somewhat hard way of answering such questions as took one no further. <small> Daniel Corkery, <a name="DCHB" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#DCHB"><cite title="source">The Hounds of Banba</cite></a> (1920) 200</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: (RJH): <i>Slip</i> can mean a young person of either sex, esp. one of small and slender build, as well as &ldquo;a soft semi-lquid mass&rdquo; or &ldquo;curdled milk&rdquo; (OED). Maybe this occasioned Joyce&apos;s variation &ldquo;broth&rdquo;. </mm> </dd></dl>
